Here is the documentation for the pneumatic cylinder:

Two pneumatic cylinders handle the suction function of the multi processing station with oven and are controlled with the help of a 3/2 way solenoid valve. In the case of the pneumatic cylinders, a piston divides the volume of the cylinder into two chambers. Differing pressure between these two chambers results in force placed on the piston, causing the piston to move. This movement corresponds to a change in volume in both chambers. Two cylinders are then mechanically connected in order to create a vacuum, which is pressure that is lower than the ambient pressure, in the vacuum gripper robot. If a cylinder is then supplied with excess pressure, the two piston rods extend, causing the volume to increase in the chamber closed by the suction cup. This increase in volume is accompanied by a drop in pressure in this chamber.
Here is the documentation for the Compressor:

A diaphragm pump supplies compressed air to the multi processing station with oven. This type of diaphragm pump consists of two chambers separated by a diaphragm; see Figure 2. A cam moves a piston in one of the two chambers up and down, causing the air in the other chamber to be drawn in or pressed out. During the downward stroke the diaphragm is pulled back, causing air to be pulled into the second chamber through the inlet valve. When the piston moves up, the diaphragm presses the air out of the pump head through the outlet valve. The compressor used in this case operates at a rated voltage of 9V DC and produces an overpressure of approximately 0.7 bar. The maximum current input of the compressor is 200 mA.

The plant is occupied with two warehouses. One takes the role as input warehouse which delivers new workpieces to the process flow. Once traveled through the several processing modules the workpieces are then stored in the second and final warehouse.
Every warehouse has a capacity of 9 workpieces. These are stored in pallets and can be transported via a crane
Here is the documentation for the light barrier:

Phototransistors are used as light barriers for the multi processing station with oven. In the process, the phototransistor conducts electricity from a certain level of brightness. However, if this luminescence threshold is exceeded, the phototransistor loses its conductivity. Together with a lens tip lamp, which faces the phototransistor, the phototransistor usually conducts electricity and can thus be used as a light barrier. A stray light hood can be used to reduce the effects of ambient light.
I'm sorry. You wanted to ask for a description, but I don't understand of which part. Could you please rephrase your request?
The sorting line is equipped with a color sensor and three different slides for storing workpieces. It revieves the workpieces from the processing station.
Everey workpiece that enters the sorting line is first send to the color sensor. This one can identify if the newly delivered workpiece is red, white or blue.
Once the color has been determined, the workpiece continues on the conveyor belt to the slides. Every slide has his own ejector, which pushes the workpiece from the belt to the slide.
The division of the workpieces to the different slides can be done according to the color (white in slide 1, ...) or the quality (workpieces without scratch in slide 2, ...)

The plant is equipped with two identical vaccum grippers. They take the transportation of workpieces between the different modules. To do so the vacuum gripper can move in 3 directions and is equipped with a compressor to create a vaccum to grip workpieces.
The first vacuum gripper moves the workpieces from the input warehouse to the processing station.
The second vacuum gripper transports the workpieces from one of the slides of the sorting line to the output warehouse

The Fischertechnik plant is an IoT demonstrator with the purpose of processing workpieces. These pieces are first stored in an input warehouse. From there they can be transported with the vacuum gripper to the processing station. This module is composed of a painting booth and a simulated polishing station. After running through the processing station a picture is taken of every workpiece leaving the module. This one is send to the Visual Recognition where the surface is analysed.

The next module the workpieces enter is the sorting line. Here the pieces are sorted according to their color. Different slides are available to store the workpieces. From there they can be transported to the output warhouse via a second vaccum gripper.

While the plant is running, sensor informaton are continuously send to the IBM cloud. There they are stored in an database and visualised over a dashboard. Furthermore this dashboard allows the user to get important information from the plant and give several commands to the different production stations.
The processing station is composed of a painting booth, a polishing station and a camera for visual inspection.
The painting booth is kind of an oven where the workpieces enter and a simulated painting process takes place. When finished, the workpieces leave again and can be moved to the polishing station.
There a polishing process is simulated. The workpieces enter the process via a turning table. After this step, the workpieces are ejected to a conveyor belt, which transports them to the next module.

On the way there, the conveyor belt stops for a short moment under a camera. This one takes a picture of the workpiece. The image is then send to the Watson Visual Recognition where the surface is checked for any damages such as scratches

values.text: You asked how to start the model factory.
First you have to fill up the input warehouse with workpieces (first row white, second red and third one blue).
Then make sure that the output warehouse is empty.
Please also check if the other modules are free of any remaining workpieces.
Then you can supply the system with electricity. To do this, the extension cable must be connected and the two power strips in the closet below the plant must be switched on.
